SIMPLE: sagacious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sagacious
<hw>Sa*ga"cious</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sagax</ets>, <ets>sagacis</ets>, akin to <ets>sagire</ets> to
perceive quickly or keenly, and probably to E. <ets>seek</ets>. See
<er>Seek</er>, and cf. <er>Presage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of
quick sense perceptions; keen-scented; skilled in following a
trail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sagacious</qex> of his quarry from so far.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, of quick intellectual perceptions; of keen
penetration and judgment; discerning and judicious; knowing;
far-sighted; shrewd; sage; wise; <as>as, a <ex>sagacious</ex> man; a
<ex>sagacious</ex> remark</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Instinct . . . makes them, many times, <qex>sagacious</qex> above
our apprehension.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Only <qex>sagacious</qex> heads light on these observations, and
reduce them into general propositions.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Shrewd</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Sa*ga"cious*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Sa*ga"cious*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sagacity</ent>⟦br⟧
